1
00:00:15,709 --> 00:00:17,037
My name is Younes

2
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:19,849
I was born in 1969

3
00:00:21,412 --> 00:00:24,120
I work as a driver

4
00:00:25,032 --> 00:00:29,120
My living conditions are average

5
00:00:31,073 --> 00:00:33,964
My education only goes up
to sixth grade in primary school

6
00:00:43,782 --> 00:00:47,740
Interviewer: In what year and how
were you detained in this prison?

7
00:00:47,844 --> 00:00:51,907
And what was the charge
you were detained for?

8
00:00:52,974 --> 00:00:55,032
In July 2016

9
00:00:57,714 --> 00:01:02,714
I was detained because I’d driven a woman alone in the car,
without a <i>mahram</i> [male guardian]

10
00:01:03,469 --> 00:01:06,776
They took my
personal papers, my ID

11
00:01:07,506 --> 00:01:11,151
I came to get the ID,
so they detained me

12
00:01:13,391 --> 00:01:16,490
I was detained for one day, then I
was whipped 100 lashes and released

13
00:01:17,219 --> 00:01:18,782
I mean, I got my ID

14
00:01:24,797 --> 00:01:26,021
In July

15
00:01:28,495 --> 00:01:32,349
I came to get my ID, and
they brought me into this place

16
00:01:33,198 --> 00:01:36,401
An ISIS member brought
me to the investigative judge

17
00:01:37,209 --> 00:01:38,433
He interrogated me

18
00:01:40,204 --> 00:01:43,980
He wrote on the slip, "Detained"

19
00:01:44,735 --> 00:01:46,818
I stayed for one day
and was whipped there

20
00:01:47,469 --> 00:01:52,000
And I walked out while
my hands were shackled

21
00:01:52,025 --> 00:01:53,312
But my eyes weren't blindfolded

22
00:01:53,937 --> 00:01:56,801
Because my charge wasn't
serious; it was just for arguing

23
00:01:57,610 --> 00:02:03,183
Before I came here, I didn't
know about these places

24
00:02:03,208 --> 00:02:05,683
The ones they detained me
in — I didn't know they existed

25
00:02:08,704 --> 00:02:11,750
Interviewer: How did you feel
when you arrived at this place?

26
00:02:12,011 --> 00:02:14,954
I arrived thinking they
would hand me my ID

27
00:02:15,006 --> 00:02:18,860
And when the investigative judge
learned I had argued with that ISIS member

28
00:02:19,537 --> 00:02:24,381
Their judge ruled that I
should spend the night in prison

29
00:02:25,318 --> 00:02:28,678
And be whipped 100
lashes, then released

30
00:02:30,046 --> 00:02:31,426
So I was released
on the second day

31
00:02:37,553 --> 00:02:40,808
When I reached the prison,
they took me to the interrogator

32
00:02:41,979 --> 00:02:45,260
He saw the slip and
asked, Why did you argue?

33
00:02:45,756 --> 00:02:48,646
I told him I didn't argue
over anything, I'm a taxi driver

34
00:02:50,105 --> 00:02:52,917
And the taxi is on the
street, anyone can ride

35
00:02:53,568 --> 00:02:55,730
Whether a woman or a man

36
00:02:56,303 --> 00:02:58,386
Anyone can ride,
that's why it's a taxi

37
00:02:58,933 --> 00:03:00,834
He said, Without a
<i>mahram</i>, it's forbidden

38
00:03:02,058 --> 00:03:05,235
She was alone, and I
argued with him, so he wrote

39
00:03:05,808 --> 00:03:08,490
On the slip: Carries
a woman alone

40
00:03:08,515 --> 00:03:10,573
And he says, We'll quit
working and sit at home

41
00:03:10,598 --> 00:03:13,906
The interrogator asked me about that, and I told
him, Yes, then we'll quit working and sit at home

42
00:03:13,931 --> 00:03:14,870
Because our work is the taxi

43
00:03:16,485 --> 00:03:20,684
He told the ISIS member,
Take him to prison

44
00:03:22,742 --> 00:03:24,305
And whip him 100 lashes

45
00:03:25,268 --> 00:03:28,081
So the ISIS member took
me to the prison upstairs

46
00:03:28,106 --> 00:03:30,190
Made me go up, and I
stayed until the second day

47
00:03:32,976 --> 00:03:37,221
They called him Abu
Hurayra, not by his name

48
00:03:37,716 --> 00:03:40,164
Each of them had a nom de
guerre they used for themselves

49
00:03:40,189 --> 00:03:42,117
Abu So-and-so... Abu Hurayra

50
00:03:42,664 --> 00:03:44,904
The one who interrogated
me was called Abu Hurayra

51
00:03:46,622 --> 00:03:48,471
Bearded ISIS member

52
00:03:48,992 --> 00:03:50,060
Interrogator

53
00:03:51,674 --> 00:03:55,372
Interviewer: What kind of
questions did the interrogator ask?

54
00:03:57,430 --> 00:03:58,966
He asked me for my ID

55
00:03:58,991 --> 00:04:01,128
He asked, What did they
take from you? I told him, My ID

56
00:04:02,422 --> 00:04:04,037
Then he asked, he
said, Why did they take it?

57
00:04:04,818 --> 00:04:07,943
I answered, I told him, Because
of a woman who was alone

58
00:04:07,968 --> 00:04:09,844
She was riding
with me in the car

59
00:04:18,542 --> 00:04:22,891
I went upstairs and sat with
a group who were detained

60
00:04:24,532 --> 00:04:26,615
I greeted them and sat down

61
00:04:28,151 --> 00:04:31,511
We talked among ourselves, but we were afraid
there might be an undercover informant among us

62
00:04:31,875 --> 00:04:34,558
No one could talk about ISIS

63
00:04:34,870 --> 00:04:39,646
For fear of the undercover
informant inside the prisons

64
00:04:40,401 --> 00:04:43,266
Who would pass the information
to ISIS if you talked about them

65
00:04:43,943 --> 00:04:47,224
Like if you said, Tomorrow the liberation
will come, or The army will arrive

66
00:04:47,589 --> 00:04:51,756
There is an undercover informant who tells
them that this person talked about them.

67
00:04:52,615 --> 00:04:56,391
That is frightening; we did not
discuss anything specific about them.

68
00:04:57,511 --> 00:05:01,026
We only talked about our release

69
00:05:04,568 --> 00:05:11,443
Interviewer: How did you feel when you were
detained during that time and for that duration?

70
00:05:12,329 --> 00:05:17,303
I arrived at noon, and the
next day at ten I was released

71
00:05:17,328 --> 00:05:19,776
But a prisoner in a room

72
00:05:20,039 --> 00:05:22,305
Meaning a door shut on you

73
00:05:23,633 --> 00:05:28,059
How would I feel?

74
00:05:38,112 --> 00:05:41,367
Interviewer: How did you
spend your time in the room?

75
00:05:42,773 --> 00:05:48,216
We just sat, slept, or talked among ourselves
about the charges brought against us

76
00:05:48,893 --> 00:05:53,971
About our charges and the
conversations going on in the hall

77
00:05:55,820 --> 00:05:59,466
Interviewer: Didn’t you
feel that one of the people...

78
00:06:03,198 --> 00:06:08,433
Wanted some information from
you, from the prisoners themselves?

79
00:06:09,763 --> 00:06:10,752
No, no

80
00:06:12,393 --> 00:06:14,294
No, there was nothing like that

81
00:06:14,319 --> 00:06:17,133
You’re afraid to talk, you know

82
00:06:17,445 --> 00:06:19,763
If your tongue
slipped with any words

83
00:06:20,206 --> 00:06:23,773
They might cut off your head
if you spoke badly about them

84
00:06:24,268 --> 00:06:27,758
I mean, they execute
the person on the spot

85
00:06:27,783 --> 00:06:30,023
Anyone who crosses the
line and talks about them

86
00:06:37,393 --> 00:06:41,247
Interviewer: Didn’t they stop
you from talking inside the room?

87
00:06:41,272 --> 00:06:45,206
We could talk about anything among
ourselves, but not about them… ISIS

88
00:06:45,969 --> 00:06:48,157
They have nothing to do with
you if you talk about something else

89
00:06:48,782 --> 00:06:53,391
Or if you get to know one of them and ask
him how many children he has, and so on

90
00:06:53,416 --> 00:06:55,006
Just conversations
to pass the time

91
00:06:55,735 --> 00:06:59,485
When we talked among
ourselves as prisoners

92
00:06:59,745 --> 00:07:01,646
Just to make the time pass

93
00:07:02,063 --> 00:07:05,344
And he talks to you and
gets some things off his chest

94
00:07:05,369 --> 00:07:06,907
To ease his mind

95
00:07:13,079 --> 00:07:17,818
The smell of the room—the
stench of sweaty bodies

96
00:07:18,756 --> 00:07:22,609
Of the detainees, some of whom
had been detained for four or five days

97
00:07:22,634 --> 00:07:24,276
Because there were
no showers to bathe

98
00:07:24,745 --> 00:07:29,016
You couldn’t bathe and the like

99
00:07:29,740 --> 00:07:33,021
And sounds,
sounds—a lot of noise

100
00:07:33,750 --> 00:07:37,110
Their voices, those of
ISIS, as they go in and out

101
00:07:37,787 --> 00:07:38,776
These sounds

102
00:07:38,801 --> 00:07:43,620
And the voices of people who
come on charges and accusations

103
00:07:44,584 --> 00:07:46,459
In many matters

104
00:07:46,615 --> 00:07:49,193
Those they bring into the
prison and those they take out

105
00:07:49,766 --> 00:07:50,860
These sounds

106
00:07:51,745 --> 00:07:55,079
And most of them here were ISIS,
the <i>Hisba</i> group [religious police]

107
00:08:01,563 --> 00:08:03,907
They brought two
meals, morning and noon

108
00:08:05,235 --> 00:08:06,954
They would bring rice
and broth, that was at noon

109
00:08:08,412 --> 00:08:09,974
And in the morning they
gave you a <i>samoon</i> [bread roll]

110
00:08:10,990 --> 00:08:12,891
Or a biscuit or some dates

111
00:08:14,011 --> 00:08:15,105
That's what they gave

112
00:08:15,130 --> 00:08:18,047
Or biscuit with dates

113
00:08:18,594 --> 00:08:20,521
Because most of them ate dates

114
00:08:21,250 --> 00:08:23,750
Dates with biscuit, or
dates with a <i>samoon</i>

115
00:08:24,792 --> 00:08:28,151
And at noon, rice

116
00:08:29,636 --> 00:08:32,448
They would bring it in large
dishes and everyone ate from them

117
00:08:35,235 --> 00:08:37,500
Interviewer: Was there a
race for the food, for example?

118
00:08:37,525 --> 00:08:41,250
To get your share from the big dish they
brought, or was there a portion for each person?

119
00:08:41,980 --> 00:08:46,068
No, no, each person got a
disposable plate just for him

120
00:08:48,803 --> 00:08:50,678
Interviewer: Was the
amount of food enough?

121
00:08:51,250 --> 00:08:54,792
There was no choice. I
spent only one night here

122
00:08:55,287 --> 00:08:58,308
And I ate one meal at noon
until the following morning

123
00:08:58,333 --> 00:09:00,365
So they brought
us biscuit and dates

124
00:09:01,303 --> 00:09:03,829
Of that small-sized biscuit

125
00:09:04,094 --> 00:09:06,672
And a little bit of dates
with it, and that's all

126
00:09:07,844 --> 00:09:09,172
After that I didn't
eat with them

127
00:09:10,917 --> 00:09:14,849
Interviewer: So were
the meals regular?

128
00:09:14,874 --> 00:09:19,172
They would bring
it at one or 2 p.m.

129
00:09:19,589 --> 00:09:21,516
And they brought
breakfast to us at 9 a.m.

130
00:09:21,594 --> 00:09:23,469
Dates and biscuit

131
00:09:23,912 --> 00:09:25,448
I didn't eat anything else here

132
00:09:26,646 --> 00:09:28,782
Even at night there
was no dinner meal

133
00:09:29,355 --> 00:09:30,474
The last meal was lunch

134
00:09:35,891 --> 00:09:39,563
If you were in great need, you
would knock on the door and call him

135
00:09:40,266 --> 00:09:41,620
You would tell him, I want
to go to the washrooms

136
00:09:41,645 --> 00:09:42,688
He would open the
door and let you out

137
00:09:43,886 --> 00:09:46,125
But it wasn't your
choice to get out

138
00:09:47,167 --> 00:09:48,547
Only at specific times

139
00:09:50,110 --> 00:09:52,636
One by one, he would take them
to the toilet and bring them back

140
00:09:54,980 --> 00:09:56,412
Interviewer: So
there was a schedule?

141
00:09:56,437 --> 00:10:00,579
If someone needed
to go in the morning

142
00:10:00,604 --> 00:10:03,417
He would knock on the door and tell
him, I just want to go to the washrooms

143
00:10:04,120 --> 00:10:06,620
He would let him out to the washrooms
and then bring him back inside

144
00:10:08,599 --> 00:10:12,636
Interviewer: How clean was
the place, and was there water?

145
00:10:13,964 --> 00:10:17,454
There was water in the place

146
00:10:18,235 --> 00:10:22,323
As for cleanliness,
the tiles were clean

147
00:10:23,079 --> 00:10:25,214
There was no mattress to sleep
on. You slept directly on the floor

148
00:10:26,714 --> 00:10:29,006
Meaning there was
no bedding under you

149
00:10:29,891 --> 00:10:30,985
On the tiles

150
00:10:31,662 --> 00:10:33,797
Interviewer: I mean the
cleanliness of the toilet?

151
00:10:35,386 --> 00:10:38,172
Whoever goes in washes his spot

152
00:10:38,719 --> 00:10:41,922
He cleans the toilet
area then leaves

153
00:10:42,990 --> 00:10:44,500
As clean as he can manage.

154
00:10:47,053 --> 00:10:55,281
Interviewer: Did you have privacy when you went to the
toilet, or was there only a short time to get in and out?

155
00:10:56,349 --> 00:11:00,099
When we went to the
toilet, we went normally

156
00:11:00,742 --> 00:11:03,242
But you had to let him
know when you needed to

157
00:11:03,267 --> 00:11:06,210
You told him and he would let you out, but
if you didn't need to, you stayed seated

158
00:11:16,419 --> 00:11:21,992
Interviewer: So when you went in, you spent
the time you needed and then came out?

159
00:11:22,435 --> 00:11:24,284
Yes, yes

160
00:11:31,627 --> 00:11:38,581
Interviewer: Some people said
they wanted to go to the toilet

161
00:11:39,359 --> 00:11:46,963
Just to get a bit of
privacy to sit by themselves

162
00:11:47,823 --> 00:11:51,808
To sit alone for a
moment inside the toilet

163
00:11:52,589 --> 00:11:56,521
Did any prisoner go out to
take advantage of that time?

164
00:11:56,546 --> 00:12:01,469
Some of them would go and stay
for 10 minutes or a quarter hour,

165
00:12:01,494 --> 00:12:03,110
and then come back

166
00:12:03,473 --> 00:12:05,791
The others would go out
and come back quickly

167
00:12:06,912 --> 00:12:09,881
I mean, in the same place where
you're sitting, your mind wanders

168
00:12:10,401 --> 00:12:13,032
In the same place you're
detained, in the prison itself

169
00:12:13,396 --> 00:12:15,766
your mind drifts
from time to time

170
00:12:21,157 --> 00:12:24,412
We were about 30
people in that room

171
00:12:29,047 --> 00:12:30,506
Interviewer: Don't
you know their names?

172
00:12:30,531 --> 00:12:34,204
There was Muhammad
and a guy called Ubaid

173
00:12:35,141 --> 00:12:37,615
And Khaled. Those were the names

174
00:12:37,849 --> 00:12:41,104
And one from the Zanjili area
and another from Yarmouk

175
00:12:41,129 --> 00:12:42,667
From those areas

176
00:12:43,188 --> 00:12:45,558
The ones next to me would
sit and I'd talk with them

177
00:12:49,855 --> 00:12:53,605
Interviewer: What were the charges
most prisoners were detained for?

178
00:12:53,630 --> 00:12:58,136
Most were paperwork-related
cases, evidence documents

179
00:12:58,474 --> 00:13:02,980
Someone who had
argued with an ISIS member

180
00:13:03,808 --> 00:13:06,542
and someone who had
given a woman a ride alone

181
00:13:06,985 --> 00:13:09,589
These are the ones with files
against them, the ones kept in this room

182
00:13:10,136 --> 00:13:11,907
I mean, light
sentences and so on

183
00:13:15,448 --> 00:13:19,094
Interviewer: How was your
relationship with the prisoners?

184
00:13:20,032 --> 00:13:24,042
Our relationship—well,
they're Iraqis from Mosul

185
00:13:24,067 --> 00:13:26,542
Prisoners together, it was good

186
00:13:28,547 --> 00:13:30,084
There were no problems with them

187
00:13:34,901 --> 00:13:36,985
Interviewer: Was
there a spy among you?

188
00:13:37,506 --> 00:13:39,641
We didn't know, but
there probably was

189
00:13:39,666 --> 00:13:42,401
Because ISIS had secret
informants everywhere

190
00:13:43,287 --> 00:13:47,792
It could be a child of seven to eight
years old acting as their informant

191
00:13:48,443 --> 00:13:51,568
or an elderly man, or a young
man—they could all be informants

192
00:13:52,662 --> 00:13:54,511
They had their own informants

193
00:13:54,954 --> 00:13:57,584
Interviewer: Did any prisoner
try to escape from the prison?

194
00:13:58,678 --> 00:14:04,146
No one could escape. Every door was
locked, so how could anyone run away?

195
00:14:05,631 --> 00:14:07,948
Wherever you went,
there was an ISIS member

196
00:14:12,730 --> 00:14:16,376
They didn't call you by
name, only by nicknames

197
00:14:16,819 --> 00:14:20,230
And this jailer was Iraqi

198
00:14:21,141 --> 00:14:22,886
Meaning he wasn't
from outside Iraq

199
00:14:23,407 --> 00:14:26,714
But from the villages and countryside
outside Mosul, not from inside it

200
00:14:27,027 --> 00:14:29,605
His accent was
from outside Mosul

201
00:14:31,011 --> 00:14:33,329
Interviewer: Didn't you see
other nationalities in this prison?

202
00:14:33,354 --> 00:14:34,970
No, I didn't

203
00:14:40,464 --> 00:14:45,282
Interviewer: What types of
torture were common in this prison?

204
00:14:45,307 --> 00:14:46,662
They flog people here

205
00:14:49,891 --> 00:14:51,323
I mean, they sentence
people to flogging

206
00:14:54,474 --> 00:14:58,615
Interviewer: What affected you more,
psychological torture or physical torture?

207
00:14:58,640 --> 00:15:03,094
Honestly, the physical torture. My back was injured
and I had to sleep on my stomach for ten days

208
00:15:03,146 --> 00:15:05,594
Because of the beating—I mean, a
hundred lashes isn’t a small number

209
00:15:11,271 --> 00:15:18,771
Interviewer: Were there specific punishments,
like <i>sukhra</i> [forced labor] for example?

210
00:15:18,796 --> 00:15:25,334
They would force prisoners
to do cleaning and other tasks

211
00:15:25,359 --> 00:15:27,443
No, they wouldn’t let
them leave the prison at all

212
00:15:28,745 --> 00:15:30,282
They wouldn’t let them out

213
00:15:32,365 --> 00:15:36,662
Interviewer: When you entered the torture
room, did you see other torture tools?

214
00:15:36,687 --> 00:15:39,032
I only saw the flogging—I
mean, the flogger

215
00:15:39,057 --> 00:15:41,271
He was standing
there flogging me

216
00:15:42,391 --> 00:15:44,240
Only the flogger was there

217
00:15:44,891 --> 00:15:48,980
Interviewer: What’s the instrument?
Witness: This is the flogging instrument

218
00:15:49,891 --> 00:15:53,901
A stick with a
leather belt—the whip

219
00:15:54,553 --> 00:15:55,438
And he hits

220
00:15:55,829 --> 00:15:57,495
With every lash he tells you,
Ask your Lord for forgiveness

221
00:15:57,496 --> 00:16:01,739
With every lash he says, Ask your Lord for
forgiveness, and I repeat, I ask God’s forgiveness

222
00:16:04,579 --> 00:16:09,448
Interviewer: How intense
were the lashes you received?

223
00:16:10,490 --> 00:16:15,178
They flogged me lightly at first,
then the force of the lashes increased

224
00:16:16,375 --> 00:16:22,156
So the body would go numb
first, then he started hitting hard

225
00:16:24,969 --> 00:16:30,776
Interviewer: Did the torture include all
prisoners, or was there discrimination?

226
00:16:33,771 --> 00:16:39,579
There were floggings and other things, but what
I know is that I was flogged and then released

227
00:16:40,360 --> 00:16:42,235
But I didn’t see other
types of torture in front of me

228
00:16:42,912 --> 00:16:47,469
But I heard about
other kinds of torture

229
00:16:48,276 --> 00:16:51,245
Like the <i>al-Adada</i> [biting
clamp] and beatings.

230
00:16:52,625 --> 00:16:55,698
There was also
kicking and slapping

231
00:16:55,723 --> 00:16:58,667
As they wished

232
00:16:59,461 --> 00:17:01,414
And according to
what the judge decided

233
00:17:02,012 --> 00:17:05,581
The judge determines the number of
lashes, a hundred lashes or fifty lashes

234
00:17:06,987 --> 00:17:10,398
And there are other
prisons with more torture

235
00:17:11,544 --> 00:17:13,315
And their torture is very severe

236
00:17:14,408 --> 00:17:19,721
Interviewer: Can you describe
the torture official who flogged you?

237
00:17:19,746 --> 00:17:23,680
His age, appearance,
the way he talked?

238
00:17:24,981 --> 00:17:26,101
His nationality?

239
00:17:26,126 --> 00:17:28,836
He was about
twenty-five years old

240
00:17:30,997 --> 00:17:34,539
He was Iraqi, from the
villages and countryside

241
00:17:35,372 --> 00:17:36,518
It was clear he was Iraqi

242
00:17:39,096 --> 00:17:40,607
And bearded

243
00:17:41,631 --> 00:17:43,636
And wearing that
Kandahari outfit

244
00:17:47,099 --> 00:17:48,349
And his accent was Iraqi

245
00:17:48,792 --> 00:17:52,412
But not from inside Mosul, rather
from outside it, as his accent made clear

246
00:17:58,766 --> 00:18:05,016
Honestly, the torture was painful. After he flogged
me a hundred lashes, my back hurt for ten days

247
00:18:05,041 --> 00:18:08,167
It hurt from the beating marks

248
00:18:09,391 --> 00:18:12,230
And my mental state
was affected a bit

249
00:18:13,271 --> 00:18:17,985
I mean, an old
man getting flogged

250
00:18:19,756 --> 00:18:22,568
They don’t respect age,
neither old nor young

251
00:18:23,482 --> 00:18:25,331
They had no respect at all

252
00:18:29,855 --> 00:18:34,412
Interviewer: As you told me, you spent ten days
sleeping on your stomach so your back wouldn’t be harmed

253
00:18:34,437 --> 00:18:39,881
During that time after you were released
from prison, how were you able to sleep?

254
00:18:39,906 --> 00:18:43,058
Didn't you have
dreams and nightmares?

255
00:18:43,579 --> 00:18:46,651
No, but my back hurt
badly from the beating

256
00:18:46,676 --> 00:18:49,412
I mean I couldn’t
sleep on my back

257
00:18:50,089 --> 00:18:53,214
And on my side I couldn’t sleep
either—I could only sleep on my stomach

258
00:18:53,761 --> 00:18:56,131
Even with medical ointments

259
00:18:57,120 --> 00:19:02,485
With a skin-healing ointment,
because the body was severely damaged

260
00:19:03,079 --> 00:19:07,818
It was as if you’d had a
severe sunburn on your back

261
00:19:08,678 --> 00:19:12,506
Gradually the skin at the beating
marks started to peel off and regenerate

262
00:19:13,209 --> 00:19:15,526
After that the skin
healed, thank God

263
00:19:21,047 --> 00:19:25,500
To this day I remember
going into the prison

264
00:19:25,525 --> 00:19:26,724
And how it happened

265
00:19:26,749 --> 00:19:28,912
How the torture
was, and the release

266
00:19:29,641 --> 00:19:32,818
That’s my story, and
it’s still on my mind

267
00:19:35,110 --> 00:19:37,167
And how I appeared before
the Investigative Judge

268
00:19:37,688 --> 00:19:40,787
And how we were taken up to
the prison and how I was flogged

269
00:19:40,812 --> 00:19:44,250
I still remember
all of this story

270
00:19:44,275 --> 00:19:48,590
From 2015 until now,
eight years have passed

271
00:19:55,205 --> 00:20:00,517
That unemployment, the psychological
state, and the pressure on us

272
00:20:01,220 --> 00:20:04,528
I used to work outside
Iraq in the oil sector

273
00:20:05,361 --> 00:20:06,793
At Qaiwan Oil Company

274
00:20:07,184 --> 00:20:10,387
I worked and traveled,
and my spirits were fine

275
00:20:10,412 --> 00:20:12,548
I didn’t use any medicine back
then, not even paracetamol

276
00:20:12,913 --> 00:20:17,236
But when ISIS came in,
we were left without work

277
00:20:17,913 --> 00:20:22,080
And the mental state
deteriorated from the oppression

278
00:20:22,105 --> 00:20:25,543
You need to provide for
your living and your family

279
00:20:26,399 --> 00:20:29,550
And children—you have
to secure your livelihood

280
00:20:30,384 --> 00:20:31,738
And we couldn’t leave

281
00:20:33,769 --> 00:20:38,691
Because they threatened us
not to go out to the oil company

282
00:20:38,716 --> 00:20:39,967
To work in oil

283
00:20:42,962 --> 00:20:45,462
And they took a
written pledge from us

284
00:20:46,217 --> 00:20:49,238
When we returned
from Iran to Erbil

285
00:20:49,263 --> 00:20:51,868
And entered Iraq—via Mosul

286
00:20:52,024 --> 00:20:54,629
They took a written pledge
that we wouldn’t go back there

287
00:20:54,654 --> 00:20:56,660
To work

288
00:20:57,832 --> 00:21:00,748
If we left, they
would kill our families

289
00:21:01,191 --> 00:21:03,170
So we stayed in
Mosul and didn’t leave

290
00:21:04,733 --> 00:21:06,790
And when the liberation
happened—we were liberated

291
00:21:13,631 --> 00:21:20,532
Interviewer: Is there a story on
your mind that you’d like to mention?

292
00:21:20,557 --> 00:21:25,896
Well, my story is that when
I came here, I’ve been sick

293
00:21:25,920 --> 00:21:28,920
I’ve been sick for
about five or six years

294
00:21:28,944 --> 00:21:30,944
Because of the psychological
trauma I went through because of them

295
00:21:30,968 --> 00:21:34,968
I mean, since ISIS came and
because of the living conditions

296
00:21:34,992 --> 00:21:38,492
I got sick, and to
this day I’m still sick

297
00:21:38,916 --> 00:21:40,916
And suffering

298
00:21:40,940 --> 00:21:44,940
I used to be a truck driver, both inside and
outside Iraq, traveling to different provinces

299
00:21:46,164 --> 00:21:48,164
I had a tractor-trailer
under my control

300
00:21:48,500 --> 00:21:50,401
I was happy and at ease

301
00:21:51,193 --> 00:21:56,480
But since ISIS came in, and even now, my
mental state has deteriorated and I'm exhausted

302
00:21:57,730 --> 00:22:02,157
How can I say this? A
person gets angry quickly

303
00:22:02,912 --> 00:22:05,724
I mean, I start
reacting to anything

304
00:22:07,599 --> 00:22:12,157
I had property, thank God

305
00:22:12,182 --> 00:22:14,136
And all that was
lost during the ISIS days

306
00:22:15,933 --> 00:22:17,782
My car burned

307
00:22:18,719 --> 00:22:20,855
And they confiscated things

308
00:22:21,480 --> 00:22:23,459
Thank God
